  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Woolloongabba has changed faster than almost any other suburb in Brisbane's inner south over the past five years. The suburb's transformation has been driven by a combination of its proximity to the CBD, the ongoing gentrification of the Gabba precinct, improved public transport links and the broader Brisbane Olympics effect on inner-city property sentiment. What was once a transitional suburb known primarily for its cricket ground and light industrial pockets is now an active residential market with a broad buyer base and meaningful price growth.</p>

      <p>The housing stock in Woolloongabba is diverse. You will find original worker's cottages and character homes on the smaller lots that define much of the residential grid, alongside more recent townhouse developments and a growing number of apartment buildings that reflect the suburb's zoning for higher density. Sellers of detached homes in Woolloongabba are operating in a market with limited supply, which works in their favour, particularly when the property has character, outdoor space, or a genuinely liveable layout.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Woolloongabba</h2>
      <p>The buyer pool in Woolloongabba is broad and has shifted notably in recent years. Young professional couples and singles dominate the apartment and townhouse market, attracted by the suburb's walkability, the improving dining and retail strip along Logan Road and Ipswich Road, and the short commute to the CBD. For detached homes, the buyer profile extends to include small families and investors who recognise that the suburb's infrastructure trajectory supports further price appreciation. Interstate buyers, particularly from Sydney and Melbourne, are increasingly active and often motivated by Brisbane's relative value compared with what they are familiar with.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Woolloongabba</h2>
      <p>For detached homes, lot size and the absence of through-traffic noise are the primary value considerations. The streets closest to the Gabba stadium and the major arterials can be affected by noise and traffic volumes, and that is reflected in buyer feedback and offer levels. Properties on the quieter residential streets, particularly those with genuine outdoor space and character elements like high ceilings, VJ walls and timber floors, command the strongest interest. Proximity to the growing cluster of cafes, restaurants and independent retailers near Boggo Road and the Gabba is increasingly a positive, as the suburb's walkability score has improved substantially.</p>

      <p>Renovation quality matters here perhaps more than in other inner suburbs, because the buyer pool includes a significant proportion of buyers who are making a lifestyle choice about where they want to live and who want a home that reflects the suburb's improving character. A well-executed renovation that respects the original architecture while adding contemporary function will consistently outperform both un-renovated originals and heavy-handed updates that have removed the character that buyers in this suburb specifically seek.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing for sale in Woolloongabba</h2>
      <p>Woolloongabba buyers tend to be urbane and visually literate. They notice presentation. The same investment in cleaning, painting, styling and photography that would make a difference in Newstead or West End applies equally here. For character homes, the most effective preparation focuses on restoring or highlighting original features rather than removing them. Polished timber floors, exposed brick, high ceilings and VJ walls are assets in this market. The campaign photography should treat these elements as selling points, not background details.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Campaign approach</h2>
      <p>Woolloongabba's improving market conditions and the broad, motivated buyer pool support auction campaigns for quality detached homes. The suburb has enough sales history now to anchor auction expectations with genuine comparables, and the competitive buyer dynamic that auction creates suits a market where multiple buyers are often pursuing the same small supply of good detached homes. Private treaty suits apartments and townhouses, where price ranges are more established and buyers are less likely to engage in competitive bidding.</p>

